snippet.textDisplay: the more Red covers this story the more curious I am as to wtf "demon" is translated from and what its literal translation (along with the connotation it has in the language). In the western world, demons permanently have the "very evil, sins-incarnate" hat while in a lot of these eastern stories it sounds more like one of many hats a spirit can have, this one just being associated with a spirit acting more violently/despicably, but a hat that can be changed nonetheless, kinda like the epithets greek deities had in a way.
snippet.textOriginal: the more Red covers this story the more curious I am as to wtf "demon" is translated from and what its literal translation (along with the connotation it has in the language). snippet.textDisplay:
After marathoning this series up til now I've decided to read Journey to the West as well! A local library has an abridged version by Anthony C. Yu so I put a hold on that and will read that as a start but I imagine the 4 revised edition volumes Anthony made are a far more comprehensive version that will properly convey the messages of Journey to the West. I'll look into checking those out as well. But! If anybody has an idea of an even better way to read this story I'm all ears!
...
No for real I'm open to suggestions. My research has uncovered like, 6 different versions of translations of this story and I'm a tad stumped as to which one(s) to look at, any suggestions will help at this point.

snippet.textDisplay: For those of you who are asking about why monkey doesn't just fly the gang. Kuan Yin gave a prophecies that the gang have to have 81 calamities before they can get the tripataka which means the gang HAVE to walk lol. The number 9 is a sacred number in Buddhism and 9*9 is 81 which 8+1=9.....yeah it's all very meta.
